        <li>I read Maslow's Religions, Values, and Peak-Experiences over a
         couple of days</li>
        <li><em>'According to Maslow there are 2 types of "peak" experiences
         &mdash; the relative and the absolute. Relative experiences
         characterize those peak experiences in which there remains an
         awareness of subject and object, and which are thus extensions of the
         individual's own experiences.'</em></li>
        <li><em>'There is a peak experience beyond the relative, the Absolute,
         which according to Maslow "are characteristic of mystical experiences,
         and are comparable to the experiences of the great mystics in history.
         <span style="font-weight: bold">They are timeless, spaceless, and
         characterized by unity, in which the subject and object become
         one.</span>"'</em></li>
        <li>Decided that Maslow's description of absolute peak experience was
         exactly what I had experienced</li>
        <li>Concluded that if I'd had an absolute peak experience that I was
         firstly immensely fortunate and secondly that apparently my higher
         needs had been and/or must now be frequently met</li>
